INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dah4300','letter','1789-09-21','Rock Landing','CT','US','David','Humphreys','','George','Washington','','individual','','But, upon receiving information from Messrs. Pickens and Osborne, that the Indians were growing very impatient to return to their homes, and that they could not possibly be detained but a few days longer, we recommenced our journey that evening.','ltr_dah4300.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume IV., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dah4301','letter','1789-09-26','Rock Landing','CT','US','David','Humphreys','','George','Washington','','individual','','On Monday last (that is to say, the day after the arrival of General Lincoln and myself), a Deputation from all the Creeks of the Tuccasee, the Hallowing, and the Tallassee Kings, waited upon us, to congratulate us on our arrival','ltr_dah4301.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume IV., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dah4302','letter','1789-09-27','Rock Landing','CT','US','David','Humphreys','','George','Washington','','individual','','McGillivray omitted to comply with his positive promise, to write to us, or come over the river, in order to explain the objections of the Chiefs to the project of the treaty which we had proposed to them','ltr_dah4302.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume IV., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dah4303','letter','1790-11-30','Lisbon','','PRT','David','Humphreys','','George','Washington','','individual','','You will be pleased to observe, by my letter to him of this date, that the Court of Lisbon, having, from a desire of opening an official intercourse with the United States, made the first advances, by appointing a Minister Resident','ltr_dah4303.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume IV., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_dah4304','letter','1786-11-01','New Haven','CT','US','David','Humphreys','','George','Washington','','individual','','The troubles in Massachusetts still continue. Government is prostrated in the dust. And it is much to be feared that there is not energy enough in that State to reestablish the civil powers.','ltr_dah4304.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume IV., Jared Sparks, 1853');
